definition: "Bilirubin is an orange-yellow tetrapyrrole pigment produced as the end product of heme catabolism. When red blood cells reach the end of their ~120-day lifespan, hemoglobin is released and the heme ring is cleaved by heme oxygenase to produce biliverdin and carbon monoxide. Biliverdin is rapidly reduced by biliverdin reductase to bilirubin. This initial product — unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin — is lipophilic and not water-soluble, so it binds to albumin for transport to the liver. In hepatocytes, bilirubin is conjugated with glucuronic acid by UGT1A1 enzyme to form conjugated (direct) bilirubin, which is water-soluble and excreted into bile. Total bilirubin = direct (conjugated) + indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin. In clinical testing, fractionated bilirubin separates these two forms — the pattern of elevation (predominantly direct vs. predominantly indirect) distinguishes hepatic from pre-hepatic causes of hyperbilirubinemia. Bilirubin is included in every CMP as a standard liver function marker."
why_it_matters: "Bilirubin has a dual clinical significance that creates a counterintuitive longevity profile. In pathological ranges, elevated bilirubin signals liver disease, bile duct obstruction, or hemolytic anemia — well-recognized medical conditions requiring investigation. But at mildly elevated levels within or just above the normal range, bilirubin is a potent systemic antioxidant, and this antioxidant activity appears to be cardioprotective. Multiple large epidemiological studies have found a significant inverse association between bilirubin levels and cardiovascular disease risk: higher bilirubin within the normal-to-mildly-elevated range is associated with lower rates of atherosclerosis, coronary artery disease, and cardiovascular mortality. The protective mechanism is biologically plausible — bilirubin scavenges peroxyl radicals and inhibits LDL oxidation in vitro, and the genetic condition of mildly elevated bilirubin (Gilbert's syndrome, affecting 5–10% of the population) is associated with significantly lower cardiovascular risk in large cohort studies. This makes bilirubin one of the few standard lab markers where the lower end of normal may not represent optimal."

