longevity_notes: "The longevity-optimal range for bilirubin inverts conventional interpretation: while values above 1.2 mg/dL may warrant investigation for liver or hemolytic pathology, values toward the upper portion of the normal range (0.6–1.2 mg/dL) are associated with lower cardiovascular risk in epidemiological studies. Values consistently below 0.4–0.5 mg/dL are associated with higher oxidative stress and cardiovascular risk in some analyses. Gilbert's syndrome — a benign genetic variant in UGT1A1 causing mildly elevated unconjugated bilirubin (typically 1.0–3.0 mg/dL) — is consistently associated with reduced cardiovascular disease, cancer, and all-cause mortality. The fractionated test is more informative than total bilirubin alone when values are elevated — predominantly indirect elevation with normal liver enzymes is reassuring (typically hemolysis or Gilbert's); predominantly direct elevation with elevated liver enzymes indicates hepatobiliary disease."
