takeaways:
- "<strong>Bilirubin is one of the most potent endogenous antioxidants in the human body — a property largely unknown outside research circles.</strong> Bilirubin scavenges peroxyl radicals at nanomolar concentrations, inhibits lipid peroxidation and LDL oxidation, and appears to function as a chain-breaking antioxidant in lipid membranes. In vitro studies suggest bilirubin's antioxidant potency rivals vitamin C and vitamin E at physiological concentrations. This antioxidant activity is likely the primary mechanism behind the epidemiological evidence linking higher-normal bilirubin to lower cardiovascular risk."
- "<strong>Gilbert's syndrome — the most common inherited cause of mildly elevated bilirubin — is associated with significantly lower cardiovascular disease risk.</strong> Gilbert's syndrome affects 5–10% of the population and results from a variant in the UGT1A1 gene that reduces bilirubin conjugation, causing mildly elevated unconjugated bilirubin (typically 1.0–3.0 mg/dL). Multiple cohort studies and Mendelian randomization analyses have found that people with Gilbert's syndrome have 30–50% lower rates of coronary artery disease and significantly lower cardiovascular mortality compared to the general population. This represents a natural human experiment showing bilirubin's cardioprotective role."
- "<strong>The pattern of bilirubin elevation — direct vs. indirect — is clinically more important than the absolute value.</strong> Direct (conjugated) bilirubin elevation indicates hepatic or post-hepatic pathology — the liver has conjugated the bilirubin but it cannot be excreted normally, suggesting hepatocellular disease, cholestasis, or bile duct obstruction. Indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin elevation with normal direct bilirubin indicates pre-hepatic pathology (hemolysis — red blood cells breaking down faster than the liver can process) or a conjugation defect (Gilbert's syndrome, Crigler-Najjar). These two patterns have completely different clinical implications, making total bilirubin alone insufficient when elevation is found."
- "<strong>Very low bilirubin is associated with higher oxidative stress in some analyses.</strong> The inverse relationship between bilirubin and cardiovascular risk extends below the midpoint of the normal range in several large studies. People with consistently low bilirubin (< 0.4–0.5 mg/dL) appear to have higher oxidative stress markers and somewhat higher cardiovascular risk compared to those in the mid-to-upper normal range. This observation suggests that optimizing antioxidant status through diet, exercise, and sleep — which modulates bilirubin levels — may have cardioprotective effects."
- "<strong>Bilirubin is included in every CMP and liver function test, making it the most accessible antioxidant biomarker available.</strong> Unlike specialized antioxidant assays, bilirubin is automatically available on any panel that includes a CMP. Tracking bilirubin trends over years — noting whether it stays in the mid-to-upper normal range, rises to potentially pathological levels, or falls toward the low-normal range — adds longevity context to routine metabolic testing at no additional cost."

