<section class="bm-section">
<h2>The Paradox of Bilirubin: Waste Product and Antioxidant</h2>

<p>For most of medical history, bilirubin was considered nothing more than a metabolic waste product — the yellow byproduct of hemoglobin breakdown that accumulates to cause jaundice when liver or biliary function fails. Its measurement in the CMP served purely as a disease detection tool: normal means the liver is clearing heme waste efficiently; elevated means something is wrong.</p>

<p>This view has been substantially revised over the past three decades. Bilirubin is now recognized as one of the most potent endogenous antioxidants in human plasma — scavenging peroxyl radicals and inhibiting lipid peroxidation at physiological concentrations. The antioxidant capacity of bilirubin was first proposed by Stocker and colleagues in 1987 and has been extensively validated since. At nanomolar concentrations, bilirubin chain-breaks lipid peroxidation reactions, protecting LDL particles and cell membranes from oxidative damage. <sup><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/3029864/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">1</a></sup></p>

<p>The epidemiological evidence followed: study after study found that people with higher bilirubin levels — particularly in the mid-to-upper normal range — had lower rates of cardiovascular disease, atherosclerosis, and all-cause mortality. The natural experiment of Gilbert's syndrome — where a common genetic variant maintains chronically mildly elevated bilirubin — provided compelling quasi-experimental evidence of bilirubin's cardioprotective role.</p>
</section>

<section class="bm-section">
<h2>Reading Bilirubin in a Longevity Context</h2>

<p>The standard CMP flags total bilirubin above 1.2 mg/dL as elevated and worthy of investigation. From a longevity perspective, the interpretation is more nuanced:</p>

<p>A person with total bilirubin of 0.2 mg/dL has very low antioxidant capacity from this pathway. A person with 0.9 mg/dL has meaningfully more. A person with 1.5 mg/dL predominantly indirect bilirubin and entirely normal liver enzymes most likely has Gilbert's syndrome and an enviably low cardiovascular risk profile.</p>

<p>The key questions for any bilirubin elevation are: What fraction is direct vs. indirect? What are the other liver enzymes doing? Is the elevation stable or progressive? These questions distinguish the benign (Gilbert's, mildly elevated hemolysis from exercise, fasting effect) from the clinically significant (hepatocellular disease, biliary obstruction).</p>

